    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 20,
    "last_activity_date" : 1265129107,
    "creation_date" : 1265129107,
    "answer_id" : 2185843,
    "question_id" : 2185789,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Using <code>Collections.unmodifiableList</code> creates a wrapper around your List. if the underlying list changes, so does your unmodifiableList's view.</p>\n\n<p>As the documentation says, Google's code creates a copy. It's a more expensive computation and consumes more memory, but if someone alters the original list, it cant affect the ImmutableList.</p>\n\n<p>Neither of these will prevent you from changing an object in a list, or it's fields, or fields of fields, etc.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 33857,
      "reputation" : 20180,
      "user_id" : 95122,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 88,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53edd8e9c033a8a0ec7f4483d52ae62a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "BobMcGee",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/95122/bobmcgee"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1265129145,
    "creation_date" : 1265129145,
    "answer_id" : 2185845,
    "question_id" : 2185789,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<ol>\n<li>No, the contained individual objects can still be modified.  A collection is really only storing <em>references</em> to the contained objects, not a full copy of every object.</li>\n<li>You can modify the list by modifying the parent Collection you called Collections.unmodifiableList(list) on.  But yes, you CAN use setDimension to change a stored list element. </li>\n</ol>\n"
